No. And I - I told him - just told him what I thought, and - I asked him one day, I said, 
do you know that you've got - got three - when we had a production meeting, and I asked him, I said do you know that you've got three skilled men, I said, working outside this factory. And he said - what do you mean. I said, well you've got a blacksmith, 
a
 carpenter and an electrician, I said, working outside of this. Well on that the works manager jumped up, and he was sitting in another chair, and he said, is that a hint to me Mr Thomas? I said, well I haven't mentioned any names, but I said apparently y
o
u know who I mean. So Barraclough of course made no - pretence, he knew it but he said - how long has this been going on then? So - Ronnie - Pearce, that's the works manager, said, it hasn't been going on at all. So I asked and I said well - who's the con
t
ractor you've got doing the masoning work? He told me, I said, yes, and I said, he's the very one that told me about these three men that's up there. So I said, from that time on - oh then he did say - Barraclough said, I don't - that's the manager, he sa
i
d, I don't know what kind of - equipment you got home Mr Thomas if you got any old mangles, he said that want repairing he said well perhaps we can do it up here. I says, you won't be buying me like that Mr Barraclough. I said, oh no. I said, you won't lu
re me that way. But I said it's hard lines, I said, I've got a boy, I said, out in Italy fighting, I said, and hard lines if these men should stay up there doing other peoples work when they should be in here. I said, that's all.
